  1. (5pt) Make a plot of total CO2 emissions over time for the U.S, China, and India. Add a few more countries of your choice. Explain what do you see.

This plot shows the total CO2 emissions over time by country for the U.S., China, India, Aruba, and Angola:

overtime <- file %>%
  filter(name == "China" | name == "India" | name == "United States of America" | name == "Aruba" | name == "Angola", !is.na(co2), !is.na(name)) %>%
  select(name, time, co2) %>%
  group_by(time) 
  
ggplot(overtime, aes(x = time, y = co2, col = name)) +
  geom_line() +
  xlab("Year") + 
  ylab("CO2 Emissions") +
  ggtitle("CO2 Emissions Over Time (by Country)")

The graph shows that for all countries, except for Aruba and Angola, CO2 emissions have increased drastically over the years. India is still increasing, but the U.S. and Chinas emissions are going down. Aruba and Angola have little emissions and their growth is almost non-existent.

  1. (5pt) Now lets analyze the CO2 emissions per capita (co2_PC ). Make a similar plot of the same countries. What does this figure suggest?

This plot shows the total CO2 emissions per capita over time for the U.S., China, India, Aruba, and Angola:

by_country <- file %>%
  filter(name == "China" | name == "India" | name == "United States of America" | name == "Aruba" | name == "Angola") %>%
  group_by(name, time) %>%
  summarize(co2_pc = sum(co2_PC, na.rm=TRUE))

ggplot(by_country, aes(x = time, y = co2_pc, col = name)) +
    geom_line() +
    xlab("Year") + 
    ylab("CO2 Emissions per Capita") +
    ggtitle("CO2 Emissions per Capita (by Country)")

The figure suggests that overtime, the CO2 per capita emissions increased drastically in Aruba but then drastically dropped, but for the other countries the CO2 per capita emissions have been steady over the years.

4 GDP per capita (50pt)

Lets look at GDP per capita (GDP_PC ).

  1. (8pt) Make a scatterplot of GDP per capita versus life expectancy by country, using data for
  2. Make the point size dependent on the country size, and color those according to the continent. Feel free to adjust the plot in other ways to make it better. Comment what do you see there.
variables <- file %>%
  filter(time == 1960, !is.na(GDP_PC), !is.na(lifeExpectancy)) %>%
  group_by(GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy) %>% 
  summarize(x = GDP_PC, y = lifeExpectancy, z = region, a = totalPopulation/1000000) 

ggplot(variables, aes(x = GDP_PC, y = lifeExpectancy)) +
   geom_point(aes(color = z, size = a, alpha = 0.5)) +
  labs(title = "GDP Per Capita vs. Life Expectancy by Country in 1960", 
         x = "GDP Per Capita", y = "Life Expectancy by Country") +
         guides(color = guide_legend(title = "Continent"), size = guide_legend(title = "Population Size (in Millions)"), alpha = "none")

The scatterplot suggests that in 1960 the GDP Per Capita and Life Expectancy in each region drastically increased overtime with a positive correlation but slowly began to plateau eventually.

  1. (8pt) Compute the average LE growth from 1960-2019 across the continents. Show the results in the order of growth. Explain what do you see. Hint: these data (data in long form) is not the simplest to compute growth. But you may want to check out the lag() function. And do not forget to group data by continent when using lag(), otherwise your results will be messed up! See https://faculty.washington. edu/otoomet/info201-book/dplyr.html#dplyr-helpers-compute.

    Average LE growth from 1960-2019 across the continents, in order of growth:

file %>%
  group_by(region, time) %>%
  filter(!is.na(lifeExpectancy), !is.na(region), time == 1960 | time == 2019) %>%  
  summarize(avgLE = mean(lifeExpectancy)) %>%
  mutate(prev = lag(avgLE, default = 0, order_by = region), growth = avgLE - prev) 
## # A tibble: 10  5
## # Groups:   region [5]
##    region    time avgLE  prev growth
##    <chr>    <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>

##  2 Africa    2019  64.1  41.5   22.6
##  3 Americas  1960  58.6   0     58.6

  1. (6pt) Show the histogram of GDP per capita for years of 1960 and 2019. Try to put both histograms on the same graph, see how well you can do it!
hist <- file %>%
  filter(time == 1960 | time == 2019, !is.na(GDP_PC))

ggplot(hist, aes(x=GDP_PC, fill = as.factor(time)))+
  geom_histogram(position='dodge') +

  ggtitle("GDP Per Capita for 1960 & 2019") +
